---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
const surgeonBody = `
  

  <!-- ============ SECTION 0: HERO ============ -->
  <header class="hero hero--with-image">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="hero-grid">
        <div class="hero-text">
          <div class="hero-eyebrow eyebrow">Surgeon Mortgages</div>
          <h1 class="display-1">Surgeon mortgage from a lender who reads surgical-group K-1 distributions, ambulatory surgery center (ASC) equity, call pay, wRVU productivity bonus, co-management agreements, and signed forward-looking attending contracts as one income picture.</h1>
          <p class="lead hero-subtitle">Working surgeons (general, orthopedic, neurosurgery, cardiothoracic, plastic, vascular, urology, ENT, ophthalmology) carry the most complex multi-source income files in U.S. medicine. A single year can include <strong>surgical group W-2 reasonable compensation plus partnership K-1 distributions ($350K&ndash;$1.2M typical for established partners), ambulatory surgery center (ASC) equity K-1 distributions ($75K&ndash;$400K from each ASC partnership the surgeon holds equity in), hospital call pay and on-call coverage compensation ($1,500&ndash;$5,000 per call shift for high-acuity coverage), wRVU productivity bonus running $35&ndash;$90 per work-RVU above baseline thresholds, surgical assistant billing, hospital service-line co-management agreement payments, robotic surgery device-related royalties and consulting for innovating surgeons, hospital sign-on bonuses ($100K&ndash;$500K for surgical specialties), and $250K&ndash;$450K of federal student loans from medical school plus 5-7 year surgical residency on income-driven repayment</strong>. Multi-entity B3-3.4-02 aggregation across the surgical practice S-corp, each ASC partnership LLC, and any imaging or lab equity entities is the qualifying default. Generalist lenders default to the W-2 portion of practice compensation and miss the surgical group K-1, ASC distributions, and call pay entirely. We aggregate the full picture.</p>
          <div class="hero-actions">
            <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call" class="btn btn-primary btn-large">Schedule a call with Jim</a>
            <a href="#income-methods" class="btn btn-secondary btn-large">See how surgeon qualifying works</a>
          </div>
          <div class="hero-trust">
            <span class="trust-dot"></span>
            <span>Broker NMLS #1072866</span>
            <span>&middot;</span>
            <span>Specialist in surgical-group K-1, ASC equity, call pay, wRVU productivity, multi-entity surgical practice, &amp; fellowship-to-attending surgeon mortgages</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <figure class="hero-image">
          <img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/1170979/pexels-photo-1170979.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1200" alt="Surgeon in operating room" loading="lazy" onerror="this.onerror=null;this.src='https://placehold.co/1200x1500/0A0E1A/E8EEFF/png?text=Surgeons';">
        </figure>
      </div>
    </div>
  </header>

  <!-- ============ STATS BAR ============ -->
  <section class="stats stats--with-image">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="stats-bar-grid">
        <div class="stats-grid">
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="stat-num">$300K-$700K</div>
            <div class="stat-label">Typical compensation range for established U.S. surgeons (orthopedic, neurosurgery, cardiothoracic top the tables; BLS median for physicians and surgeons combined sits at $239,200+ but specialty data places surgeons substantially higher)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="stat-num">$250K-$450K</div>
            <div class="stat-label">Typical surgical residency student loan burden (5-7 year residency adds debt accumulation on top of medical school baseline)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="stat-num">B3-3.4-02</div>
            <div class="stat-label">Fannie Mae rule allowing multi-entity K-1 aggregation across surgical practice S-corp + ASC partnerships + ancillary entities</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="stat-num">$35-$90</div>
            <div class="stat-label">Per work-RVU productivity bonus rate range for surgical specialties (higher than non-surgical physicians at $25-$75)</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <figure class="stats-bar-image">
          <img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/4173251/pexels-photo-4173251.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1000" alt="Surgical team in operating room" loading="lazy" onerror="this.onerror=null;this.src='https://placehold.co/1000x750/0A0E1A/E8EEFF/png?text=Surgical';">
        </figure>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ LEDE ============ -->
  <section class="lede-section">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <p class="lede">Stairway Mortgage qualifies working surgeons on the full income picture &mdash; <strong>hospital W-2 base salary plus wRVU productivity bonus and call pay under Fannie Mae B3-3.1-01 variable income for hospital-employed surgeons, S-corp W-2 reasonable compensation plus K-1 distributions under B3-3.4-02 for surgical group partners and practice owners, multi-entity B3-3.4-02 aggregation across the surgical practice S-corp plus each ASC partnership LLC plus any imaging center or lab ancillary equity for surgeons with established ancillary ownership, partnership K-1 distributions from physician-owned hospitals and specialty group partnerships, hospital service-line co-management agreement payments (medical service agreements, MSA) structured as 1099-NEC continuing professional services income, surgical device consulting and royalty income from device manufacturers for innovating surgeons (Medtronic, Stryker, Zimmer Biomet, Smith+Nephew, Arthrex), signed forward-looking attending employment contracts under Physician/Doctor Loan programs for fellowship-finishing surgeons (qualifying on the new attending position up to 60-90 days pre-start), Form 1084 cash-flow addbacks for surgical equipment depreciation under IRC Section 167 and Section 179 immediate expensing on operating room equipment and surgical instruments at the surgical group entity level, and federal student loan IDR payments under B3-6-05 from Federal Student Aid PAYE/SAVE/IBR plans documented through servicer statements</strong>. A first-year academic surgical attending finishing fellowship, an established hospital-employed surgeon with substantial call pay coverage, a surgical group partner with both practice K-1 and ASC equity distributions, an orthopedic surgeon with ASC equity plus device consulting, and a senior multi-location surgical practice owner with co-management agreements each get qualified using methods that fit their actual structure. We pick the right door before we quote. Or skip ahead: browse <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">every loan program</a>, run numbers on <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-calculator/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">100+ mortgage calculators</a>, or check <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/current-rates/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">today&apos;s rates</a>. For the parent hub and other medical professional paths, see our <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/medical-professionals/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">medical professionals mortgage hub</a>.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #1: KEY FACTS ============ -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="text-align: center; max-width: 760px; margin: 0 auto;">
        <div class="eyebrow">01 &middot; Surgeon mortgage at a glance</div>
        <h2>Key facts every surgeon should know before applying for a mortgage.</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="key-facts-grid">
        <div class="key-fact-card">
          <div class="key-fact-num">Multi-entity</div>
          <p class="key-fact-body">Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.4-02/analyzing-returns-partnership-or-s-corporation" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.4-02</a>, K-1 distributions from the surgical practice S-corp PLUS each ASC partnership PLUS any imaging or lab ancillary entity aggregate as qualifying income. Each entity needs 2-year 1120-S or 1065 history. Generalist lenders see one K-1 and miss the rest.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="key-fact-card">
          <div class="key-fact-num">ASC equity</div>
          <p class="key-fact-body">Per <a href="https://www.ascassociation.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Ambulatory Surgery Center Association (ASCA)</a>, more than 6,000 Medicare-certified ASCs operate in the U.S. Physician-owned ASC models give surgeons equity in surgical facility income separate from professional fees. ASC K-1 distributions typically run $75K&ndash;$400K per ASC for established surgical partners.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="key-fact-card">
          <div class="key-fact-num">ACS</div>
          <p class="key-fact-body">The <a href="https://www.facs.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">American College of Surgeons (ACS)</a>, founded 1913, is the largest U.S. surgical professional association. <a href="https://www.abms.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">ABMS</a> board certification through specialty boards (American Board of Surgery, American Board of Orthopaedic Surgery, etc.) supports established surgeon qualifying.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="key-fact-card">
          <div class="key-fact-num">B3-6-05 IDR</div>
          <p class="key-fact-body">Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-6-05/monthly-debt-obligations" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-6-05</a>, actual IDR payment from <a href="https://studentaid.gov/manage-loans/repayment/plans/income-driven" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Federal Student Aid plans</a> counts in DTI. Surgical residency (5-7 years) extends loan accumulation; PAYE/SAVE payments often $0&ndash;$2,000/month against $250K&ndash;$450K balances vs $2,500&ndash;$4,500 the 1% rule imposes.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #2: ROLE-STAGE SOLUTIONS ============ -->
  <section class="professions-section section-tinted">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="text-align: center; max-width: 720px; margin: 0 auto;">
        <div class="eyebrow">02 &middot; Where you are in your surgical career</div>
        <h2>Surgeon mortgage solutions for every career stage.</h2>
        <p>Each stage of a surgical career has its own qualifying logic. A first-year orthopedic surgeon finishing fellowship has a different mortgage path than an established surgical group partner with ASC equity, or a senior multi-location surgical practice owner with co-management agreements and device consulting income.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="professions-grid">

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">01</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">First-year attending surgeon post-fellowship (Years 1&ndash;2)</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Just completed surgical fellowship. Signed first attending contract with hospital system or surgical group. Sign-on bonus and loan repayment ramping, wRVU bonus still building."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Annual income $325K&ndash;$550K W-2 attending plus $100K&ndash;$400K sign-on</li>
            <li>Specialty bonuses (psychiatry &lt; ortho &lt; neuro &lt; cardiothoracic)</li>
            <li>Federal student loans $250K&ndash;$450K on PAYE or SAVE</li>
            <li>Physician/Doctor Loan with signed-contract qualifying OR Conventional Jumbo with B3-6-05</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See first-year surgeon mechanics</span>
        </a>

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">02</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">Established hospital-employed surgeon (Years 3&ndash;7)</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Established attending in hospital or health-system employment. Substantial call pay coverage. Full wRVU productivity bonus running."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Annual income $450K&ndash;$750K W-2 + wRVU + call pay</li>
            <li>Hospital call pay $1,500&ndash;$5,000 per shift (trauma, neuro, OB)</li>
            <li>2-year wRVU history under B3-3.1-01 variable income</li>
            <li>Conventional Jumbo or Physician Jumbo Loan</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See employed surgeon mechanics</span>
        </a>

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">03</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">Surgical group partner with ASC equity (Years 5&ndash;12)</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Made partner in surgical group practice. Partnership distributions are primary income. Possibly equity in ASC and other surgical facilities."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Annual income $550K&ndash;$1.2M through W-2 reasonable comp + K-1 + ASC K-1</li>
            <li>Multi-entity B3-3.4-02 aggregation across practice + ASC entities</li>
            <li>Each entity needs 2-year 1120-S or 1065 history</li>
            <li>Conventional Jumbo with multi-entity documentation</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See partner + ASC mechanics</span>
        </a>

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">04</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">Senior multi-entity surgical partner (Years 8&ndash;15)</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Senior partner with established practice K-1 plus multiple ASC equity positions plus possibly imaging center equity and hospital service-line co-management agreements."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Annual income $750K&ndash;$1.8M through multi-entity K-1 + co-management</li>
            <li>Co-management 1099 income from hospital service-line agreements</li>
            <li>2-3+ ASC partnership K-1s aggregated under B3-3.4-02</li>
            <li>Conventional Super-Jumbo or asset-depletion complement</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See senior partner mechanics</span>
        </a>

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">05</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">Multi-location surgical practice owner / surgeon-entrepreneur</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Senior practice owner with multi-location surgical practice possibly including owned ASC, imaging center, or specialty hospital. May include device consulting or royalty income."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Annual income $1M&ndash;$3M+ through multi-entity ownership</li>
            <li>Device consulting and royalty 1099 income</li>
            <li>Multi-entity B3-3.4-02 across surgical entities + ancillary</li>
            <li>Super-jumbo or asset-depletion against accumulated multi-entity reserves</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See practice owner mechanics</span>
        </a>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #3: INCOME CALCULATION METHODS ============ -->
  <section class="section" id="income-methods">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div class="eyebrow">03 &middot; The qualification mechanics</div>
        <h2>How we calculate qualifying income for your surgeon mortgage.</h2>
        <p>Four methods cover almost every surgeon file we&rsquo;ve closed. The right method depends on your career stage, whether you maintain hospital employment vs surgical group partnership, the role of ASC equity ownership, and how co-management agreements and device-related income fit your structure.</p>
      </div>

      <h3>Method 1 &mdash; Hospital W-2 + wRVU + call pay (the employed-surgeon default)</h3>
      <p>For surgeons in hospital or health-system employment. Hospital base salary qualifies under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.1-01</a> as continuous W-2 income with 24-month average. wRVU productivity bonus qualifies as variable income with 24-month average plus current-year trending. Hospital call pay (typically $1,500&ndash;$5,000 per call shift depending on specialty and acuity &mdash; trauma surgery, neurosurgery, and OB-Anesthesia command the highest rates) qualifies as variable employment income with 24-month history. Combined hospital W-2 + wRVU + call pay often runs $450K&ndash;$750K for established employed surgeons.</p>

      <h3>Method 2 &mdash; Surgical group S-corp with W-2 + K-1 (the partner-track path)</h3>
      <p>For surgeons in private group practice partnership. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.4-02/analyzing-returns-partnership-or-s-corporation" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.4-02</a>, qualifying income combines S-corp W-2 reasonable compensation (typically $250K&ndash;$400K for surgical partners) plus K-1 distributions from <a href="https://www.irs.gov/forms-pubs/about-form-1120-s" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Form 1120-S</a> with 2-year history. Form 1084 cash-flow addbacks recover non-cash depreciation on surgical practice equipment under <a href="https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/167" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRC Section 167</a> and Section 179 expensing on operating equipment and surgical instruments.</p>

      <h3>Method 3 &mdash; Multi-entity aggregation (surgical group + ASC + ancillary)</h3>
      <p>The signature qualifying pattern for established surgeons. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.4-02/analyzing-returns-partnership-or-s-corporation" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.4-02</a>, K-1 distributions from multiple entities aggregate as qualifying income with 2-year history per entity: (1) the surgical group practice S-corp K-1; (2) each ASC partnership LLC K-1 (often 1-3 ASC partnerships for established orthopedic, GI, pain, and ophthalmology surgeons); (3) imaging center or specialty hospital equity K-1s where applicable. Each entity must have 2-year 1120-S or 1065 history and documented ownership percentage. Multi-entity surgical files routinely involve $200K&ndash;$700K of K-1 income that generalist lenders miss entirely.</p>

      <h3>Method 4 &mdash; Co-management and device consulting 1099 supplementary</h3>
      <p>For surgeons with hospital service-line co-management agreements (orthopedic service-line, cardiovascular service-line, cancer surgical service-line) and device consulting income. Co-management agreements (medical service agreements, MSA) pay surgeons for operational and quality leadership of hospital service-lines, typically structured as 1099-NEC. Device consulting income from medical device manufacturers (Medtronic, Stryker, Zimmer Biomet, Smith+Nephew, Arthrex, J&amp;J DePuy Synthes) for surgeons providing design input, training programs, or speaking engagements qualifies as 1099-NEC. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.3-02/income-analysis-self-employed-borrowers" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.3-02</a>, these 1099 streams aggregate as continuing Schedule C self-employment with 2-year history.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #4: DARK SECTION ============ -->
  <section class="per-diem-section per-diem-section--bg" style="background-image: url('https://images.pexels.com/photos/4173251/pexels-photo-4173251.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1800');">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="max-width: 760px;">
        <div class="eyebrow eyebrow-light">04 &middot; What generalist underwriting misses</div>
        <h2 style="color: var(--paper);">The income most lenders refuse to count on a surgeon file.</h2>
        <p style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.78);">Six income streams that show up consistently on working surgeon files and that generalist lenders typically either ignore, mis-categorize, or refuse to apply correctly. Each one is documentable; the lender just has to read the multi-entity surgical practice structure, ASC equity, call pay arrangements, and device consulting properly.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="dark-grid">
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">A</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Ambulatory Surgery Center (ASC) equity K-1 distributions</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Per <a href="https://www.ascassociation.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">ASCA</a>, more than 6,000 Medicare-certified ASCs operate nationally with physician-owned models common in orthopedics, GI, pain management, ophthalmology, and plastic surgery. Established surgical partners commonly hold equity in 1-3 ASC partnerships. K-1 distributions typically run $75K&ndash;$400K per ASC. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.4-02/analyzing-returns-partnership-or-s-corporation" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">Fannie Mae B3-3.4-02</a>, ASC K-1s aggregate with the surgical practice K-1 with 2-year history per ASC. Generalist lenders see "partnership distribution from outside entity" and refuse, missing $150K&ndash;$800K.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">B</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Surgical wRVU productivity bonus (higher per-wRVU than physicians)</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Surgical specialties command higher per-work-RVU productivity bonus rates than non-surgical physicians. Per-wRVU rates typically run $35&ndash;$90 for surgical specialties (vs $25&ndash;$75 for non-surgical) reflecting the higher complexity and revenue generation of surgical care. For an established orthopedic surgeon generating 11,000&ndash;14,000 wRVUs annually above threshold, surgical productivity bonus runs $150K&ndash;$500K&mdash;commonly 25&ndash;40% of total compensation. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">B3-3.1-01</a>, this qualifies as variable income.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">C</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Hospital call pay and on-call coverage compensation</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Hospital call pay for surgeons covering trauma, OB, neurosurgery, ICU surgical consultation, and OB-Anesthesia commonly runs $1,500&ndash;$5,000 per call shift, with high-acuity centers paying premium rates. Annual call pay for surgeons with substantial call coverage commitments commonly totals $60K&ndash;$250K. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">B3-3.1-01</a>, hospital call pay qualifies as variable W-2 income with 24-month average. Generalist lenders may treat call pay as "irregular" and exclude entirely.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">D</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Hospital service-line co-management agreements (MSA)</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Established surgeons frequently hold hospital service-line co-management agreements (medical service agreements, MSA) where the surgeon provides operational, quality, and clinical leadership for a hospital service-line (orthopedic, cardiovascular, cancer surgical) in exchange for compensation typically structured as 1099-NEC. Annual MSA compensation runs $50K&ndash;$200K per agreement. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.3-02/income-analysis-self-employed-borrowers" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">B3-3.3-02</a>, co-management 1099-NEC qualifies as continuing Schedule C self-employment with 2-year contract history.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">E</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Surgical device consulting and royalty income</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Innovating surgeons commonly hold consulting and royalty agreements with medical device manufacturers (Medtronic, Stryker, Zimmer Biomet, Smith+Nephew, Arthrex, J&amp;J DePuy Synthes, Globus Medical). Income includes 1099-NEC consulting fees ($25K&ndash;$200K annually), 1099-MISC royalty payments on device design contributions ($10K&ndash;$500K annually depending on device commercial success), and Sunshine Act reportable speaking and training income. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.3-02/income-analysis-self-employed-borrowers" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">B3-3.3-02</a>, device-related income aggregates as continuing self-employment with 2-year history.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">F</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Forward-looking signed contracts (fellowship-to-attending)</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Surgeons finishing fellowship training can qualify on forward-looking signed attending contracts up to 60-90 days pre-start under Physician/Doctor Loan programs. The signed contract documents future attending income before fellowship completion. Particularly important for surgeons because surgical residency plus 1-2 year fellowship pushes attending entry to age 31-35, making pre-start home purchase coordination critical for life-stage timing. Specialty-trained surgeons coming out of fellowship commonly close at $1M-$2M+ price points.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #5: LOAN PROGRAM MATRIX ============ -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="text-align: center; max-width: 720px; margin: 0 auto;">
        <div class="eyebrow">05 &middot; Match the program to your surgical situation</div>
        <h2>Which loan program fits your surgeon mortgage situation.</h2>
        <p>Seven loan-program categories cover essentially every surgeon file we&rsquo;ve closed. The mix tilts toward Multi-Entity S-Corp Conventional Jumbo (for partner-level surgeons with ASC equity) and Physician/Doctor Loan (for fellowship-finishing and first-year surgeons).</p>
      </div>
      <div class="loan-program-grid">

        <div class="loan-program-card">
          <h3 class="loan-program-name">Multi-Entity S-Corp Conventional Jumbo</h3>
          <ul class="loan-program-points">
            <li>Surgical group partners with ASC equity and ancillary entities</li>
            <li>Aggregated K-1 distributions across entities under B3-3.4-02</li>
            <li>2-year 1120-S or 1065 per entity with ownership documentation</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="loan-program-tag">Best for: Partner with ASC equity</div>
        </div>

        <div class="loan-program-card">
          <h3 class="loan-program-name">Physician/Doctor Loan</h3>
          <ul class="loan-program-points">
            <li>MD/DO with low-down or no-down structure</li>
            <li>No PMI, IDR-friendly DTI, signed-contract qualifying</li>
