  <!-- ============ H2 #6: INDUSTRY CONTEXT ============ -->
  <section class="section section-tinted">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div class="eyebrow">06 &middot; Why this mortgage requires specialty expertise</div>
        <h2>The surgeon mortgage in context: 6 forces shaping how surgeons qualify.</h2>
        <p>Surgical income sits at the intersection of accelerating surgical specialty shortage and signing bonus inflation, the ambulatory surgery center growth trajectory and physician ownership models, private equity consolidation of surgical specialties, robotic surgery and device-related income, the malpractice insurance economics for high-acuity surgical specialties, and ACS/ABMS specialty board credentialing. Each force shapes what a working surgeon&rsquo;s qualifying picture looks like.</p>
      </div>

      <h3>Force 1 &mdash; Surgical specialty shortage and signing bonus inflation</h3>
      <p>Per <a href="https://www.aamc.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">AAMC</a> physician workforce projections, the U.S. faces particularly acute surgical specialty shortages in general surgery, vascular surgery, neurosurgery, cardiothoracic surgery, and rural surgical coverage. The shortage drives signing bonus inflation: surgical specialties now offer $100K&ndash;$500K signing bonuses, multi-year loan-repayment-assistance packages, and aggressive wRVU bonus structures. Hospital systems compete aggressively for surgical talent through guaranteed-comp structures during the productivity ramp-up period (Years 1-2 post-fellowship). The mortgage implication: first-year attending surgeon income substantially exceeds the trailing fellowship income by 6-10x.</p>

      <h3>Force 2 &mdash; ASC growth and physician ownership models</h3>
      <p>Per <a href="https://www.ascassociation.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Ambulatory Surgery Center Association (ASCA)</a>, more than 6,000 Medicare-certified ASCs operate in the U.S., serving as the preferred surgical setting for orthopedic, ophthalmologic, gastroenterology, pain management, and increasingly cardiovascular procedures. Physician-owned ASC models give surgeons equity stake in surgical facility revenue separate from professional fees. The mortgage implication: established surgeons in ASC-friendly specialties (orthopedic, GI, ophthalmology, pain, ENT, urology) commonly hold equity in 1-3 ASC partnerships generating $75K&ndash;$400K each in K-1 distributions annually that must be properly aggregated under B3-3.4-02 for qualifying.</p>

      <h3>Force 3 &mdash; Private equity consolidation of surgical specialties</h3>
      <p>Private equity has aggressively consolidated surgical specialty practices over the past decade, particularly orthopedic (OrthoLazer, USPI-affiliated platforms), ophthalmology (EyeCare Partners, Quigley Eye Specialists), dermatology, urology (Solaris Health), gastroenterology (USDP, GI Alliance), and anesthesiology platforms. PE-backed roll-ups typically purchase practices, convert surgical partners to employed positions with multi-year retention contracts plus earnout structures tied to practice performance, and aggregate ASC ownership at the platform level. The mortgage implication: surgeons at PE-backed practices may have complex income transitions from K-1 partner to W-2 employed with earnout payments &mdash; we coordinate qualifying around the transitional structure.</p>

      <h3>Force 4 &mdash; Robotic surgery and device-related income</h3>
      <p>The expansion of robotic surgery platforms (Intuitive Surgical da Vinci across multiple specialties, Stryker Mako orthopedic, Medtronic Hugo, J&amp;J Ottava) and minimally invasive surgical innovation has created consulting and royalty income streams for surgeons participating in device development and clinical training. Annual device-related income for innovating surgeons can run $50K&ndash;$500K+ depending on device commercial success and surgeon&rsquo;s role. Sunshine Act reporting documents these payments transparently. The mortgage implication: device consulting and royalty income aggregates under B3-3.3-02 as continuing self-employment with 2-year history.</p>

      <h3>Force 5 &mdash; Malpractice insurance economics</h3>
      <p>Surgical specialties carry substantially higher malpractice insurance costs than non-surgical medicine. Neurosurgery, OB-GYN, OB-Anesthesia, cardiothoracic surgery, and orthopedic spine surgery routinely face $100K&ndash;$200K+ annual malpractice premiums. State tort environment, claim history, and procedure mix drive variation. Malpractice insurance costs flow through practice operating expenses, reducing practice net profit before K-1 distribution, and represent a major cost line in surgical group economics. The mortgage implication: practice net income after malpractice expense is the qualifying base &mdash; underwriters review the practice 1120-S for proper expense classification.</p>

      <h3>Force 6 &mdash; ACS and ABMS specialty board credentialing</h3>
      <p>The <a href="https://www.facs.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">American College of Surgeons (ACS)</a>, founded 1913, is the largest U.S. surgical professional association. <a href="https://www.abms.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">ABMS</a> board certification through surgical specialty boards (American Board of Surgery, American Board of Orthopaedic Surgery, American Board of Neurological Surgery, American Board of Thoracic Surgery, and other ABMS member boards) supports established attending surgeon qualifying. Fellowship Council and Accreditation Council for Graduate Medical Education (ACGME)-accredited fellowship completion documents subspecialty credentialing. The mortgage implication: board certification status documents long-term income stability for underwriters.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

