        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">12</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My specialty is OB-Anesthesia with high call burden. How is that file?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">OB-Anesthesia attendings typically combine hospital W-2 base with significant 24/7 OB call coverage compensation and wRVU productivity bonus. Annual call pay for OB-Anesthesia commonly runs $80K&ndash;$200K. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.1-01</a>, the multi-stream W-2 with call pay aggregates as variable income with 24-month average. Total comp commonly $450K&ndash;$700K. We document the hospital call schedule and pay history.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">13</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My practice was acquired by a PE-backed surgical platform. How does that affect qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Post-acquisition surgeons typically transition from partner K-1 income to W-2 employed income with multi-year retention contracts (commonly 5-10 year terms) plus earnout payment structures tied to practice performance. The W-2 portion qualifies under B3-3.1-01. Earnout payments may qualify as continuing income with proper documentation. Pre-acquisition K-1 history supports the established surgeon income case. We coordinate qualifying around the transitional structure with your practice CFO.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">14</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Are mortgage rates higher for surgeons?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Base conventional and jumbo rates are the same for surgeons as for any other borrower at the same credit profile. Physician/Doctor Loan rates are typically within 0.125&ndash;0.375% of standard jumbo pricing in exchange for low-down structure and no PMI. Multi-Entity Super-Jumbo Conventional pricing for established surgical partners with ASC equity is competitive. We compare programs case-by-case.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">15</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My spouse is also a physician or surgeon. How does that affect us?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Two-MD households produce strong joint qualifying. Both files combine as co-borrowers with W-2s, RVU bonuses, K-1 distributions if practice partners, ASC equity if applicable, and IDR payments. Two-MD households commonly qualify for $3M&ndash;$6M mortgages even with significant combined medical school student loan balances when both spouses are on IDR with documented servicer payments.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">16</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My recent ASC equity acquisition is only 18 months old. Can the K-1 count?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">For Conventional B3-3.4-02 qualifying, typically you need 2 years of K-1 history per entity. Workarounds: (1) qualify primarily on established entities (surgical practice + older ASC) with 2+ year history, treating the new ASC as supplementary; (2) wait additional months for the 2-year history; (3) qualify on overall multi-entity package where the new ASC is a modest portion. We model the trade-offs.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">17</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">How does the IRS Section 199A QBI deduction affect me?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Surgical practice is a Specified Service Trade or Business (SSTB) under <a href="https://www.irs.gov/businesses/qualified-business-income-deduction" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRC Section 199A</a> with phase-out at $191,950-$241,950 for single filers (2024 indexed). Established surgeons sit well ABOVE the phase-out where the QBI deduction zeroes out. The deduction&rsquo;s absence reduces the AGI line that some underwriters use for affordability. We coordinate with your CPA to document the right numbers.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">18</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My practice has retained earnings across the surgical S-corp plus 2 ASCs. Are those usable as reserves?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Generally yes if accessible. Retained earnings in each entity&rsquo;s business accounts count as reserves if you have the ability to distribute them. Documented via Schedule L (balance sheet) on each entity&rsquo;s 1120-S or 1065. For mature multi-entity surgical files, aggregated retained earnings across all entities represent significant reserve strength supporting super-jumbo qualifying.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">19</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I work at a nonprofit hospital. Does PSLF affect my surgeon mortgage qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Indirectly but importantly. If your hospital qualifies for <a href="https://studentaid.gov/manage-loans/forgiveness-cancellation/public-service" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">PSLF</a>, your IDR payments count toward forgiveness AND count in DTI under B3-6-05 during the qualifying years. After 120 qualifying payments the remaining balance discharges. For surgeons with 5-7 year residency plus fellowship plus first attending years, PSLF eligibility often aligns with the early-career home purchase window favorably.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">20</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Are there mortgage programs specifically for surgeons?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Physician/Doctor Loan products extend to surgeons (MD/DO designation). No surgeon-specific products exist beyond that. What matters more is finding a broker who understands multi-entity B3-3.4-02 K-1 aggregation across surgical practice + ASC entities, B3-3.1-01 variable income for W-2 + wRVU + call pay, B3-3.3-02 self-employment for co-management and device consulting, B3-6-05 IDR documentation, and signed-contract qualifying for fellowship-to-attending transitions.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">21</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My ASC investment is structured as an LLC partnership. Does that change qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">No &mdash; Fannie Mae B3-3.4-02 covers both S-corp K-1 (Form 1120-S, Schedule K-1) and partnership K-1 (Form 1065, Schedule K-1) aggregation equivalently. ASC LLCs typically file Form 1065 partnership returns and issue K-1s to physician-owners. We pull the LLC&rsquo;s 1065 with 2-year history, the K-1 documenting your ownership and distribution, and qualify the same way as S-corp distributions.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">22</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m a J-1 visa surgeon on a waiver. Does that affect mortgage qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">J-1 visa surgeons working under a J-1 waiver (3-year service commitment in underserved area in exchange for waiver of 2-year home country residency requirement) qualify the same as U.S. citizen surgeons with proper documentation. The waiver service commitment supports income continuity for the 3-year period. We document the waiver status, employment contract, and work authorization for the underwriter.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">23</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My specialty (cardiothoracic) has $180K of annual malpractice premiums. Does that affect qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Malpractice insurance is a practice operating expense, not personal expense. It flows through the practice 1120-S or 1065 income statement reducing practice net profit before flowing to your K-1. The 2-year practice income history under B3-3.4-02 represents your qualifying base after malpractice expense. The expense itself doesn&rsquo;t affect personal DTI.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">24</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">When should I start the mortgage conversation relative to a home purchase?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Ideally 120&ndash;150 days before you intend to make an offer for partner-level surgeons with multi-entity structures. Surgeon files often take longer than standard files because of multi-entity 1120-S and 1065 review across practice + ASCs + ancillary entities, hospital employment contract review for sign-on, wRVU, and call pay treatment, possible co-management agreement documentation, device consulting 1099 documentation, and signed-contract qualifying for fellowship-to-attending transitions. For fellowship-finishing surgeons, starting the conversation in early spring gives proper runway.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">25</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Why do generalist lenders refuse surgeon files when there&rsquo;s clearly significant income?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Three reasons: (1) Multi-entity K-1 aggregation under B3-3.4-02 across surgical practice + ASC + ancillary entities is unfamiliar to generalist lenders defaulting to single-entity W-2 borrowers; (2) call pay, wRVU bonus, co-management 1099, and device consulting streams get mis-categorized as "irregular" or "ancillary" income; (3) signed-contract pre-start qualifying for fellowship-finishing surgeons under Physician/Doctor Loan programs is unfamiliar to lenders without specialty expertise. The income is all real and verifiable &mdash; multi-entity surgical files just need a broker who reads the structure correctly.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

