        <div class="eyebrow">12 &middot; What "right door first" looks like</div>
        <h2>Surgeon mortgage, structured right.</h2>
        <p>Established orthopedic surgical partner, 11 years post-fellowship, multi-entity ownership structure. Surgical group S-corp with $295K reasonable-comp W-2 plus $545K in practice K-1 distributions. Equity in two ambulatory surgery center partnerships generating $185K and $135K respectively in annual K-1 distributions ($320K aggregate ASC K-1). Plus medical device consulting 1099-NEC averaging $95K combined from Stryker (orthopedic implant design input) and Arthrex (arthroscopy training program). Plus hospital service-line co-management agreement for orthopedic service at $65K annually as 1099-NEC. Total annual income $1.32M split across one W-2, three K-1 streams (practice plus 2 ASCs), and two 1099-NEC streams (device consulting plus co-management). Plus $215K of remaining federal student loans from medical school plus 5-year orthopedic residency plus 1-year sports medicine fellowship, on PAYE with documented servicer payment of $1,275/month. The first lender looked at the W-2 plus surgical practice K-1 only ($840K combined), refused the ASC K-1s as "outside ancillary partnership income not central to professional practice," called the device consulting "speaking fees not professional services income," excluded the co-management 1099 as "supplementary not continuing," applied the 1% rule to the student loan balance ($2,150/month theoretical vs $1,275 actual), and offered $1.45M maximum. We pulled the surgical practice 1120-S returns with the K-1, both ASC partnership 1065 returns with K-1s and ownership documentation, the Stryker and Arthrex consulting agreements with 2-year payment history, the hospital co-management MSA contract, the IDR servicer statement showing the $1,275 PAYE payment, the ABMS orthopedic surgery board certification, and the state medical licensure. Ran the W-2 under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue);">Fannie Mae B3-3.1-01</a>, aggregated the surgical practice K-1 plus both ASC K-1s across all 3 entities under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.4-02/analyzing-returns-partnership-or-s-corporation" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue);">B3-3.4-02</a> multi-entity treatment, aggregated the device consulting plus co-management 1099s under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.3-02/income-analysis-self-employed-borrowers" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue);">B3-3.3-02</a> as continuing Schedule C self-employment with 2-year history, and used the actual $1,275 IDR payment under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-6-05/monthly-debt-obligations" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue);">B3-6-05</a>. Total qualifying income: $1.28M after addbacks and normalization. Approved at $3.4M conventional super-jumbo for a Boca Raton home. Closed in 56 days. Multi-entity surgical files are exactly what conventional super-jumbo with B3-3.4-02 is built for &mdash; you just need a broker who knows how to document them.</p>
